Our brains are hardwired to seek evidence in our life that confirms what we already believe is true. It’s called confirmation bias.

The good news is that if you believe today is a good day, life is awesome, and you’re doing a great job… then your brain will find examples in your day to confirm that!

The bad news? If you woke up today deciding it was going to be an awful day, your life is crumbling, and everyone is out to get you… your brain will find examples to confirm that is true instead.

So friend…

Which lens will your choose to view the world through today?

The choice is yours.

I haven’t stopped smiling since the moment I woke up today. Stepping into this new decade just feels different.

I feel a peaceful sense of confidence.

Not the kind that boasts or brags to show off or fit in with others, but the kind that feels more like a quiet and comforting whisper to self saying, “I see you, I trust you, and I love you just as you are.”

I’m not sure how else to describe it.

Reflecting back in my journal this week, I had an unexpected wave of grief wash over me. While I’ve been excited for this big milestone birthday for a while, I felt a twinge of sadness for my younger self spending all those years without the wisdom I have today. 

But I guess that’s how wisdom works, much of it comes with age.

While other people may try to bestow their wisdom upon you, sometimes lessons have to be learned the long and hard way for yourself.

It’s taken me three decades on this earth to finally learn the biggest lesson of them all: I am worthy and enough just as I am.

Finally, I believe it deep in my core.

And I’m choosing to trust that everything, even this obvious yet hard truth, is happening right on time.

I’m so grateful for the gift of another year surrounded with so much goodness, including my sweet husband who surprised me during my morning journaling with a flaming cake and cautionary balloon. (swipe to see)

⏰Is it time to break up with your scale?

Here’s the thing, scales aren’t bad…

They are a hunk of metal and plastic, there is nothing moral about them. They are simply an inanimate object that's job is to provide data.

That said, our relationship with this totally neutral object may be anything but neutral.

Ever had a morning where you’re feeling fine and good until you hop on the scale and it shows you a number higher than you hoped to see, only for it to ruin the rest of your day?

Yep, been there.

But the scale isn’t meant to measure your worth and how you feel about yourself.

Our society has been conditioned to put more “weight” into what it says, pun intended, than is actually helpful for our overall health. In fact, weight isn’t even the best measure of health in the first place! 

So, dear friend, today on the podcast I’m sharing 7 ways to measure health WITHOUT a scale.

If you are exploring the idea of breaking up with scale, while also still wanting to focus on your health, this one's for you!

“What am I going to miss about this season one day when it’s over?”

I’ve been thinking about this question a lot lately.

I half jokingly told @courtdehoff that one day when @backroadcowgirls gets big-time, I’ll miss being able to walk through an airport without being recognized.

(It’s called ✨MANIFESTING✨)

As a dreamer, I tend to get caught up in dreaming of big bold audacious dreams far away. It’s great, but constantly living in the future has a tendency to steal my attention from being present in the moment.
 
Aware of that pitfall, one of my guideposts for this year has been to romanticize my life, not the one I’m creating for myself in the future, but the one I’m living in right here and now.
 
Whether the season you’re in is going through school, living with your parents, raising an infant, being single, caring for a loved one, building a home, starting a business, or whatever it may be…

I truly believe (even amidst the hard parts) there is something about this season you’re going to look back on and remember fondly.
 
Instead of reflecting back and wishing you had it appreciated it more, asking yourself that one simple question helps you be nostalgic about it in real time.

It allows you to savor the present moment, root yourself in gratitude, and romanticize the life you’re currently living.

If you’re ready to savor life more, tune into episode 84 of the Climbing with Coach Kiah Podcast where I share five ways you can start to romanticize your life today, too.

What does “cowgirl” mean to you?

As I sat down with my podcast microphone today to record a show for this week, I had flashbacks to little Kiah.

I remember never feeling fully cowgirl like my cousins because I didn’t own my own horse. I could barely rope a roping dummy, let alone an actually steer horseback. I never competed in any rodeo events and it wasn’t until last year when I finally owned my very first cowgirl hat.

I’ve felt imposter syndrome many times in my life throughout school and my career, but the truth is that I felt it early on even in my family.

Little Kiah wanted so desperately to fit in. To not only be a rancher, but a real “cowgirl” in every sense of the word.

I wanted so desperately to be able to walk into the western wear store and find a pair of rhinestone studded jeans that actually fit my hips or tall boots that fit my calves.

I wanted to be able to saddle a horse, pull myself on top without needing a fence to stand on, and ride fearlessly without admitting to myself that horses still made me uneasy.

I felt like a fraud, like an imposter, in my own family, on my own ranch. As if someone would find out that I wasn’t “Twisselman” enough, whatever that even means.

What would little Kiah think of me now?

Still no horse to call her own, still just as equally unskilled with a rope, and yet packing her bags to head to Fort Worth, Texas to celebrate being one of the 2023 honorees for @cowgirlmagazine’s #Cowgirl30Under30.

Turns out that not fitting in wasn’t really a bad thing all along. After all, as @brenebrown so wisely teaches, the opposite of fitting in is belonging.

Little Kiah just had to learn how to belong to herself first before she could confidently embrace being her own unique kind of cowgirl.

May we all learn to cultivate the confidence to step into that version of ourselves, whatever she may look like.

Tune in to this week’s Climbing with Coach Kiah podcast on Wednesday for more of my thoughts on this 🎙️💛

If you can relate and find shopping stressful, here are 5 tips I hope can help.

1️⃣ Decide it’s going to be a fun experience before you get there. If you go in dreading it, odds are it will be dreadful and the opposite is also true!

3️⃣ Bring multiple sizes into the dressing room with you. Every brand fits differently!

4️⃣ Shop at retail stores (like @farm_supply!) with great customer service staff who can help you exchange sizes and explore options!

5️⃣ Remember, it doesn’t matter what the size is on the tag. Clothes are made to fit YOU, not the other way around.

Growing up, I always struggled with seeing exactly where I fit with the family ranch.

Horses weren’t really my thing. I never competed in rodeo. I loved the cattle, but wasn’t sure my future would be raising them.

I loved the ranch with my whole heart, but I felt called to do something different. To step away, spread my wings, and explore beyond the fence lines where I grew up.

Ever since I was a little girl, my grandpa always told me I needed to do something with people.

I’ll be honest, for a long time I had no clue what that even meant or how on earth I could translate that into an actual career. 

Fast forward and my love of people and storytelling has taken me far beyond the ranch to become a life coach, motivational speaker, and now co-host of a TV show. 

This last spring, we interviewed my Grandpa Darrell for one of our @backroadcowgirls episodes and I asked him, “Grandpa, how do I fit?”

This is wisdom he shared.

“The ranch is like growing a crop. It gives you roots, so that’s your roots. Wherever you go, whatever you do, that’s your roots. And so you just feed those roots. Protect the idea of the ranch and the romance of the old west. Preserving that part of the idea into the future is probably the most important thing you can do.”

My Grandpa passed away in October and a week from today I’ll be emceeing his memorial service at the ranch.

He always understood my dreams better than anyone. It’s like he knew the seeds that were planted in my heart even before I did.

I’ve finally found my place.

It’s not horseback or working a cattle chute like I once thought it needed to be. It’s rooting myself in the values I was raised with and using my voice to share stories that connect with the hearts of people.

@backroadcowgirls is more than just a passion project @courtdehoff and I dreamed up over pasta and wine. It’s our own unique way of continuing our family legacies.

As we prepare to film the official pilot episode next month, I know grandpa is smiling down with pride knowing all along that I fit, I just had to discover how for myself.

My family has been ranching in rural California for seven generations.

Over the weekend we had our annual spring cattle branding. The sun was shining, the grass was green, and four generations of our family came together for a day of ranch work.

It wasn’t until one of our friends mentioned it that I even realized… 

The majority of the crew working that day was women. My mom, my nieces, my cousins, my aunts, and my 89 year old grandma.

In an industry that has been traditionally male dominated, it’s so empowering to see all the capable, hard-working ranch women in my family confidently own their place in agriculture.

On our ranch, it doesn’t matter
If you’re a cowboy or a cowgirl,
If you’re old or young,
If you’re horseback or on the ground,
If you’re a newbie or been around,
If you’re on the fence or behind the camera…

Everyone plays a role and it takes all kinds to keep it alive for the next generation.

I’m proud of my ranching heritage and while I might not be the one with my boots on the ground ranching day to day, I’m proud of my part in keeping this legacy alive.

Contrary to what we’ve been taught to believe, confidence has very little to do with what we LOOK like. 

Confidence is a feeling and feelings are born of THOUGHT, not circumstance.

That’s good news!

Because that means no matter what you look like, you can start THINKING your way into feeling more confident right now.

No, you don’t need to lose weight.
No, you don’t need to have flawless skin.
No, you don’t need to get cosmetic surgery.
No, you don’t need to (fill in the blank).

What you need is a perspective shift.

How? Start by celebrating yourself as you are right now today.

We spend so much of our mental energy tearing ourselves down, picking apart our flaws, and doubting our worth.

(Don’t beat yourself up for it, negativity bias is a part of the human condition. Annoying, I know.)

But when was the last time you actually gave yourself some kudos?

When was the last time you looked back and celebrated just how far you’ve come?

When was the last time you looked in the mirror and found gratitude for the body you call home?

Here’s a question I encourage you to answer today:

➡️What am I grateful for right now about myself, without changing a single thing?

Jot it down in a journal, a note on your phone, or heck, better yet, comment it below!

After you answer, check in with yourself.

How did that feel?

Congratulations, you just dropped a coin into your self-confidence bank.

Don’t discount the impact of these small but mighty perspective shifts. It may surprise you just how powerful they can be!

Here are 5️⃣ tips for engaging with an audience while speaking on stage! 👇

1️⃣ GET THEM MOVING
If you can get the audience up on their feet (like dancing!) or active in some way, they will be more attentive and energized to hear you speak.

2️⃣ MAKE THEM FEEL SOMETHING
Emotions are powerful tools for connection. Surprise them, make them laugh, heck, make them cry! But whatever you do, don’t let the something you make them feel be boredom. 

3️⃣ GET VULNERABLE
Why the heck should they care who you are and what your message is? Earn their trust and give-a-darn but telling your story in a way they can connect with on a deeper level while feeling seen, understood, and less alone.

4️⃣ MAKE IT RELEVANT
The #1 question you should always be answering for the audience is, “What’s in it for me?” You may be the one with the microphone, but your talk is not about you. It’s about the minds and hearts in the room that your message can connect with.

5️⃣ STICK AROUND
Really want to connect with the audience and show them you care? Don’t just talk and walk. Hang out a while, engage in other parts of the event, and give them a chance to chat with you to share their own story.

It’s story time…

My recent work trip to Cancún was a journey that healed my inner child in ways I didn’t anticipate.

As I unpacked my wildly colorful suitcase of outfits for the week, authentically showed up as emcee the women’s retreat, and confidently wore my swimsuit at the pool, it occurred to me…

This version of myself - my most confident, vibrant, and magnetic version - was the hero I had searched for all along as a little girl.

Someone who could exist unapologetically in her body, unphased by unrealistic beauty standards, and allow her whole self to take up space, be seen, and express herself.

I was doing it. The years of work I’ve put in to heal my relationship with myself and my body were paying off.

I flew home riding a high of deep gratitude, grounded by the healing experience.

That was until I woke up the next morning to a message in my Facebook inbox…

It read, “I think you're really great! Have followed you for about 3 years and it seems like you're gaining the weight back!!! You had done so wonderful, I really hope you'll be able to get back on track!! Good luck!!”

It gutted me.

Even after such an incredible and healing week in Mexico, all it took was one message from a stranger to snap me right back to the insecure little girl inside of me, as if to say, “See. No matter how successful you are or how much work you do to love and accept yourself, you’ll never be worthy or enough if you exist in a larger body.”

In hindsight, I’m glad the message came when it did.

Because what my inner child really needed was to be reminded that even when the world continues to show up as it always has, so focused on the size and appearance of our bodies, she can still choose radical self-love and self-acceptance instead. 

Listen to episode 117 of the Climbing with Coach Kiah Podcast for the full story and hear why I’m choosing to press pause on new episodes for a bit.

P.S. Please be clear, I have nothing but compassion and love for the woman who sent me the message, someone who is walking her own body image and self-love journey.

Our move: the long story.

We’re moving away from my hometown on the Central Coast of California this week.

We’ve been back here for 5 wonderful years and I’ve cherished every moment of it.

My husband accepted a new job taking us back to his home state of Kentucky.

While we’re so excited for what’s next for us and our family, it’s been really hard to say goodbye.

We’ve faced a lot of deep grief about this move.

The truth is that it’s hard to close a good chapter.

Even when you know it’s the right move for you and your family.

The average home in our California town sold for $950,000 this year. 

Meanwhile, the average home in the Kentucky town we’re moving to sold for $242,000 this year.

Purchasing a home and growing our family was getting harder to pencil out if we stayed.

There’s so much we’re going to miss, but we made the bittersweet decision to leave.

While we’ll be further from our family in California, we’ll be closer to our family in Kentucky.

We’ll be able to afford a home, raise a family, and still be able to come back and visit often.

It’s such an odd feeling to hold so much grief and gratitude at the same time.

Here’s to starting over. 🫶
